The North Eastern Arms Compact Carbine Stock (CCS) is the ultimate Personal Defense Weapon (PDW) solution. A collapsible stock; shortening the overall length of the rifle approximately 2 7/8” inches compared to a traditional M4 stock.
The CCS has been designed with the professional in mind allowing for quick deployment into the firing position. The CCS is a 2 position stock and can simply be pulled into the fully extended position without the need for manipulation and collapsed by depressing the locking mechanism. The CCS is made out of 6061 T6 Aluminum and 4140 steel to ensure its durability in the harshest environments. The aluminum features a matte black Cerakote finish and the steel components have been treated with our ARC+ Nitriding giving an added layer of corrosion resistance and durability. The CCS comes as a complete drop-in unit containing stock, stock adapter, buffer tube, spring and modified full auto bolt carrier/buffer. The CCS is compatible with most mil spec AR-15’s.

title: For Sale/Trade:  VZ24 Mauser Chaco War Contract (Rare Bolivian)
location: Mt. Pleasant, SC, South Carolina, United States
postcontent:
IMPORTANT: I am based in WV, but I will be traveling to South Carolina in mid-February. I'll be in that area for some time before going back. If interested, please let me know before then (around Feb. 14) so that I can bring it down. 

I have a Bolivian Contract VZ24 Mauser for sale or trade. As you know, (or maybe do a bit of looking around on the internet) this rifle is extremely rare. Only 101,000 ever produced in the caliber 7.65x53 (Argentine) for the Chaco War. Boliva has also never released their VZs (sent originally from the Czechs and "approved" by the Nazis who later used them in Stalingrad and other places after capturing Czech factories). It is also an extremely well-made weapon. 

Gunsmith inspected. Good headspace and bore. Caliber measured to be 7.65x53 (only Bolivan Contracts have this). Numbers don't match and crest has been scrubbed -- BUT for all the good in the world the Condor Bird marking still remains. It is very small but escaped scrubbing. Bolt cycles perfectly and the gun is a shooter as well as collector's prize. 

Wonderful and beautiful rifle, but I'm wanting something else and cannot afford to keep it and add a new beauty. 

Ask for pics! Armslist cannot process the high MB.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Springfield 1903
postcontent:
1903 Springfield in great shape with all correct marking on the wood, barrel and receiver. First issued in 1918 for WWI and the serial number matches that manufacture date. After WWI was returned to the arsenal to be reworked and stored. Received and new barrel in 1942 as reflected and confirmed by the stamps on the barrel. All markings in the stock reflect that this is the original stock for this rifle with all proper markings and stamps. The barrel inside is bright and shinny and the lands and groves are like new, showing very little use. I have fired this rifle and it functions flawlessly. It has the long range rear sights. Original sling dated 1944. I got this from the man that carried it during WWII and brought it home. It has been in his safe until he sold it to me.

I took this rifle to the cabalas gun library experts in Phoenix to have it confirmed and evaluated.  

I will consider trades for guns of equal value or for cash and trade or multiple gun trades. Similar rifles are listed on Armslist for at or around the same price and they are not in near this condition.

title: For Sale:  High Quality .223 reloads, 55g FMJ-BT
postcontent: I reload each winter and over the past several years, I've reloaded more than I have consumed. I now have a good bit of excess .223 I can part with. If you're one of the weekend rock 'n' rollers that goes through alot of .223/5.56, this may be your lucky day.  My reloading is done by hand, no automated equipment whatsoever. I've been using the same powder charge for 30+ years (IMR 4198 21.0 grains). No sense in changing something that performs flawlessly.  Back in the good ole 20-inch AR days, my loads chrono'd at 3120 FPS. My cases are trimmed to specifications, not reloaded as-is, like some well-known southeastern outfits. My ammo is resized with a RCBS small-base 223 die, not a 5.56 one. It will chamber in any 223 AR platform. I visually inspect each piece of brass about 6-8 times through its reload cycle and have several quality control parameters I manage. The price of reloading components significantly affects the costs and therefore, my asking price. Willing to sell in lots of 500 rounds for $200 cash (40 cents a round), I'll do a small price break on a 1000 round lot ($380). Meet/pickup in West Knox only

postcontent:
I honestly don't know much about this rifle. It apparently belonged to a Florida sheriff's office SWAT team that moved from bolt action rifles for their snipers to AR-10 type rifles and these were surplused out a few years back. I picked it up on a whim when I bought a couple of their surplus pistols. 

This thing has the wear you'd expect of a used surplus police sniper rifle. It likely wasn't shot much because the barrel is perfect but it looks like it has wear from being stored in a case in the back of a moving patrol car for years. Meaning: If you look at the handle on the bolt for instance, you see wear in the bluing and wear on the edges of the deputy's paint job. 

The stock is a Houge stock and I have no idea what the scope is but it is a variable power scope that is dead-on-balls accurate and clean and bright. I took this thing to the range ONCE and the rounds hit wherever the crosshairs were without any effort at all (and I'm not a long range shooter by any means). The name of the scope may be under whatever wrap is on the scope but it doesn't appear to be one of the nicer, expensive brands but it sure is crisp and accurate whatever it is. Make your trade offers or cash offers based on the rifle and I'll throw the scope in on the deal free because I'm too attached to this paint job to unwrap it to investigate the scope and I may just keep the whole rifle if no cool trade offers come in. BiPod and sling included and I'll even throw in the .308 rounds on the stock and about 50rds more. 

The paint job appears to be just spray paint so a little Citristrip should take this right off if you're not a fan of the paint job (which I think is the coolest part). 

Looking mostly for trades but feel free to make a cash offer.

The TAVOR® is a perfect fusion of an ordnance grade steel receiver coupled to a Mil-Spec cold hammer forged barrel and encased into a high-impact strength polymer uni-body with exceptional situational ergonomics. The ultra-compact form factor allows for easy transitions in close quarter situations…or even in your favorite deer blind. The bullpup design moves the center of gravity of the rifle closer to the users’ body allowing for more instinctive aiming and improved acquisition time to target. This innovative design also allows for a full length barrel, which means no loss of down range ballistic accuracy. Near and far range accuracy is enhanced by the minimized recoil provided by a non-lubricated long stroke gas piston system. With the exception of a hand-specific locking bolt, the rifle is completely ambidextrous allowing for easy left-hand conversion of the operating handle, ejection port, fire-control safety, sling swivel receptacles and fore-mounted accessory Picatinny rail. The TAVOR® is supplied with IDF-tested and approved magazines – but you can also use your own AR-15/M16 style magazines.
